{"content":[{"content":{"params":{"text":"<p><strong>PEST MANAGEMENT</strong><br />\nThe following are the recommended pest management practices for okra:</p>\n\n<p><br />\n<strong>Weed Management Practices</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>Do manual weeding</li>\n\t<li>Off-bar and hill up 30 days after planting</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>INSECT PESTS AND DISEASE CONTROL</strong></p>\n\n<p></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>Practice Integrated Pest Management (IPM)</p>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>Prune and burn old, and infected leaves at regular intervals to control diseases.</p>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>Use healthy seeds  to control viruses </p>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>Observe strict sanitation</p>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>Practice crop rotation to avoid nematode damage</p>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>Use organic manure</p>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p>Common insect pests and diseases of okra and their management: </p>\n\n<p><strong>a. Cotton Stainer </strong><em> (Dysdercus cingulatus L.)</em></p>\n"},"library":"H5P.AdvancedText 1.1","metadata":{"contentType":"Text","license":"U","title":"Untitled Text","authors":[],"changes":[]},"subContentId":"6f6fc309-0bff-4fed-a0ca-2beca54b4eaf"},"useSeparator":"auto"},{"content":{"params":{"contentName":"Image","alt":"Cotton Stainer","file":{"path":"images/image-lgZ3BAX6.png","mime":"image/png","copyright":{"license":"U"},"width":1748,"height":1240}},"library":"H5P.Image 1.1","metadata":{"contentType":"Image","license":"U","title":"Untitled Image","authors":[],"changes":[]},"subContentId":"1457b37d-44dc-4ff9-bbe6-380d8d8c7e4c"},"useSeparator":"auto"},{"content":{"params":{"text":"<p></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>Collect the insects including eggs and burn or bury these into the soil</p>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>Use overhead irrigation to reduce insect population</p>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>b. Leaf hopper </strong> <em>(Amrasca biguttula Ishida)</em></p>\n"},"library":"H5P.AdvancedText 1.1","metadata":{"contentType":"Text","license":"U","title":"Untitled Text","authors":[],"changes":[]},"subContentId":"01fae4f0-09da-489a-9bde-270f1c494caf"},"useSeparator":"auto"},{"content":{"params":{"contentName":"Image","alt":"Leaf Hopper","file":{"path":"images/image-mpt0LM1f.png","mime":"image/png","copyright":{"license":"U"},"width":1748,"height":1240}},"library":"H5P.Image 1.1","metadata":{"contentType":"Image","license":"U","title":"Untitled Image","authors":[],"changes":[]},"subContentId":"cd423f6c-7269-4688-8b8e-9a424784c4f3"},"useSeparator":"auto"},{"content":{"params":{"text":"<p></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>Irrigate the area planted with okra twice a week to prevent or minimize drying of the leaves sucked by the pests </p>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>Prune infested leaves and properly dispose them.</p>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p>c. Cercospora Leaf Spot</p>\n"},"library":"H5P.AdvancedText 1.1","metadata":{"contentType":"Text","license":"U","title":"Untitled Text","authors":[],"changes":[]},"subContentId":"9001e54a-e1a1-423b-b8a2-aebcc94689b1"},"useSeparator":"auto"},{"content":{"params":{"contentName":"Image","alt":"Leaf Spot of Okra","file":{"path":"images/image-ilVf13Yx.png","mime":"image/png","copyright":{"license":"U"},"width":1748,"height":1240}},"library":"H5P.Image 1.1","metadata":{"contentType":"Image","license":"U","title":"Untitled Image","authors":[],"changes":[]},"subContentId":"f424629e-a64d-4422-86e0-938c1deb6c29"},"useSeparator":"auto"},{"content":{"params":{"text":"<p></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>Gather all infected leaves as soon as the symptoms start to appear. </p>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>To avoid transferring the disease to healthy leaves, burn infected leaves or bury these outside the area</p>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>Remove some leaves (leaf thinning) so that the ultra violet rays of the sun can penetrate in between the leaves and kill the pathogens </p>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>Avoid mono-cropping</p>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n"},"library":"H5P.AdvancedText 1.1","metadata":{"contentType":"Text","license":"U","title":"Untitled Text","authors":[],"changes":[]},"subContentId":"ad12f395-63ec-4773-8b23-cd179c9c7f4a"},"useSeparator":"auto"},{"content":{"params":{"media":{"params":{"contentName":"Image","file":{"path":"images/image-aYL7o1ow.jpg","mime":"image/jpeg","copyright":{"license":"U"},"width":300,"height":225},"alt":"Leaf Hopper"},"library":"H5P.Image 1.1","metadata":{"contentType":"Image","license":"U","title":"Untitled Image","authors":[],"changes":[]},"subContentId":"c4a7c653-5ba3-414f-a4bb-248edf0bcfc4"},"solutionLabel":"Click to see the answer.","taskDescription":"<p>Which insest pest it is?</p>\n","solutionText":"Leaf Hopper"},"library":"H5P.GuessTheAnswer 1.4","metadata":{"contentType":"Guess the Answer","license":"U","title":"Guess the Answer","authors":[],"changes":[],"extraTitle":"Guess the Answer"},"subContentId":"805590a5-d806-4dde-99b3-e8c7387667f1"},"useSeparator":"auto"}]}